            {"question": "How does RAII relate to exception safety?", "answer": "RAII objects release resources in their destructors, which run during stack unwinding. This provides at least the basic exception safety guarantee automatically — no resource leaks even when exceptions are thrown.", "topics_covered": ["Memory Management", "Exception Handling"]},
            {"question": "Why must move constructors be noexcept for std::vector to use them?", "answer": "vector needs the strong exception guarantee during reallocation. If move might throw, a partially-moved state can't be rolled back. noexcept move lets vector safely transfer elements. Without it, vector copies instead.", "topics_covered": ["Move Semantics", "STL", "Exception Handling"]},
            {"question": "How does false sharing relate to cache lines and atomic operations?", "answer": "When two threads modify different atomic variables on the same cache line (~64 bytes), each modification invalidates the other core's cache line. This causes expensive coherency traffic even though the data is logically independent. Fix: alignas(64) padding.", "topics_covered": ["Concurrency", "Cache & Performance"]},
            {"question": "How does the vtable mechanism interact with multiple inheritance?", "answer": "With multiple inheritance, an object has multiple vptrs — one for each base class with virtual functions. Each vptr points to the corresponding base's vtable. Casting between bases adjusts the this pointer (thunk). Virtual inheritance adds additional indirection.", "topics_covered": ["OOP", "Memory Management"]},
