            {"question": "How does copy elision interact with move semantics?", "answer": "Copy elision is better than moving — it constructs directly in the destination (zero copies, zero moves). That's why returning std::move(x) is wrong: it forces a move when NRVO would have given zero-cost construction. C++17 mandates elision for prvalue returns.", "topics_covered": ["Move Semantics", "Templates"]},
