            {"question": "How does the strict aliasing rule affect compiler optimization?", "answer": "Strict aliasing lets the compiler assume pointers of different types don't alias the same memory. This enables keeping values in registers longer, reordering loads/stores, and eliminating redundant reads. Violating it causes bugs that only appear at -O2.", "topics_covered": ["Pointers", "Cache & Performance", "Debugging"]},
            {"question": "How does PIMPL relate to dynamic linking and ABI stability?", "answer": "PIMPL hides implementation behind a pointer. Since the pointer size never changes, adding/removing private members doesn't change the class layout, preserving ABI. This is critical for shared libraries (.so/.dll) where recompilation of users isn't possible.", "topics_covered": ["Design Patterns", "Compilation & Build"]},
            {"question": "How do concepts (C++20) improve on SFINAE for template constraints?", "answer": "SFINAE works by making substitution failures silently remove overloads — the mechanism is indirect and error messages are terrible. Concepts directly express requirements with named predicates, give clear error messages, and participate in overload resolution (more constrained wins).", "topics_covered": ["Templates", "Standard Evolution"]},
