            {"question": "How do cache effects influence container choice?", "answer": "vector (contiguous) has excellent spatial locality — prefetcher predicts sequential access. list/map nodes are scattered in memory — each access may be a cache miss. Even for 'O(1) insertion', vector often wins due to cache effects. Always profile.", "topics_covered": ["STL", "Cache & Performance"]},
            {"question": "How does memory ordering in atomics relate to hardware architecture?", "answer": "x86 has a strong memory model (most operations are already acquire/release). ARM/POWER have weak models requiring explicit barriers. seq_cst inserts full barriers everywhere (expensive on ARM). Using relaxed/acquire-release reduces barrier overhead on weak architectures.", "topics_covered": ["Concurrency", "Low-Level Systems"]},
            {"question": "Why is type erasure related to both OOP and templates?", "answer": "Type erasure uses OOP internally (virtual base class + templated derived class for concrete types) but presents a value-semantic, non-OOP interface externally. Templates provide the 'any type' capability; virtuals provide the runtime dispatch.", "topics_covered": ["Design Patterns", "Templates", "OOP"]},
            {"question": "How do sanitizers relate to undefined behavior categories?", "answer": "ASan catches memory UB (overflow, use-after-free). UBSan catches language UB (signed overflow, shifts, alignment). TSan catches concurrency UB (data races). MSan catches uninitialized reads. Together they cover most common UB sources.", "topics_covered": ["Debugging", "Core Language"]},
            {"question": "How does const-correctness interact with thread safety?", "answer": "In C++11, const member functions are expected to be thread-safe (callable from multiple threads simultaneously). If a const function modifies a mutable member, that member should be atomic or protected by a mutex. The standard library follows this convention.", "topics_covered": ["Core Language", "Concurrency"]},
            {"question": "What is the connection between placement new and custom allocators?", "answer": "Custom allocators (arena, pool) allocate raw memory. Placement new constructs objects at specific addresses within that memory. The allocator handles memory lifecycle; placement new handles object lifecycle. Destructors must be called manually.", "topics_covered": ["Memory Management", "STL"]},
            {"question": "How do inline variables (C++17) solve the static initialization order fiasco?", "answer": "Inline variables can be defined in headers without ODR violations. Combined with constinit (C++20), they ensure compile-time initialization, eliminating the fiasco entirely. Before C++17, the Meyers Singleton pattern was the workaround.", "topics_covered": ["Core Language", "Compilation & Build"]},
            {"question": "How does object slicing relate to value categories and move semantics?", "answer": "Slicing occurs when a derived object is copied/moved into a base object — the derived part is lost. This happens with pass-by-value. Pass by reference (const Base&) or pointer (Base*) prevents slicing. unique_ptr<Base> preserves polymorphism.", "topics_covered": ["OOP", "Move Semantics", "Smart Pointers"]},
